-- в”Ђв”Ђ Windmill в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Open-source, code-first platform that turns Python, TypeScript, Go, Bash, and SQL scripts into internal tools, automated workflows, and scheduled jobs.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$open-source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free self-hosted; Enterprise from USD120 per month plus per-seat add-ons$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2022, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Small (roughly 20-25 employees)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Paris, France and San Francisco, California, US$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Windmill Review 2026: Open-Source Internal Tools and Workflow Platform$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Explore Windmill's code-first orchestration platform for internal apps, workflows, and job scheduling, including open-source and Enterprise pricing.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Windmill is an open-source, code-first orchestration platform for building internal software, founded in 2022 by Ruben Fiszel and backed by Y Combinator, Bessemer Venture Partners, and Gradient Ventures. The company is dual-based in Paris and San Francisco and has grown to roughly 20-25 employees, serving a reported 4,000-plus organizations including more than 300 enterprise customers, while being SOC 2 Type II certified. Windmill's core idea is to let engineers and technical teams turn ordinary scripts written in Python, TypeScript, Go, PHP, Bash, or SQL directly into production-ready internal tools, without requiring a proprietary SDK or vendor lock-in. The platform automatically generates user interfaces for scripts and flows, so a script can become a usable internal app with minimal extra work. Workflows are represented as DAG-based flows that model task dependencies, and Windmill markets itself as one of the fastest orchestrators available, aimed at replacing a mix of cron jobs, ad hoc scripts, and heavier workflow engines like Airflow or Temporal for many internal-tooling use cases. Collaboration is built around Git, with entire workspaces version-controlled, and permissions and shared resources configurable for teams working together on the same scripts and flows. Enterprise-oriented features include role-based access control, single sign-on, secret management, audit logging, and SAML with group synchronization. Windmill can be run entirely self-hosted using Docker, AWS Fargate, or Kubernetes, or consumed via Windmill's cloud offering. Pricing follows an open-core model: the free, open-source self-hosted tier supports unlimited executions, up to 50 users, three workspaces, 10 GiB of object storage, and community Discord support, with some caps such as 10 SSO users and 100 triggered emails per day. The paid Enterprise tier starts at 120 per month and adds unlimited workspaces and executions, distributed S3-backed dependency caching, unlimited audit logs and job retention, advanced observability via Prometheus and OpenTelemetry, agent workers, SSH execution support, and 24/7 priority support with a 3-hour response guarantee. Enterprise pricing scales with add-ons for developer seats (20 per month each), operator or external JWT users (10 per month each), and standard or native subworkers (50 per month each). There is no usage-based metering beyond these seat and compute add-ons. Windmill is typically compared to tools like Retool, n8n, and Airflow, differentiating itself through its emphasis on plain code, high execution throughput, and a genuinely open-source free tier suitable for self-hosting at scale.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '029723bb-0e7c-43dd-958e-73d6dbd7933b';

